    </nav>
    
    <div class="bg-white rounded-3xl container-shadow max-w-4xl mx-auto p-6 md:p-10">

        <!-- Header Section -->
        <header class="text-center mb-8">
            <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 leading-tight">
                Assessing Students' Awareness of Educational Sustainability
            </h1>
            <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-semibold mt-2 text-gray-700">in Higher Education Institutions</h2>
            <p class="text-md sm:text-lg text-gray-600 mt-4 font-medium">
                Noor Aziatul Afifah, Ahmad Adib, Nik Ahmad Nabihan
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-1">Business School, Universiti Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia</p>
        </header>

        <!-- Image Section -->
        <div class="my-8 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden">
            <img src="https://placehold.co/1000x500/A7D2A9/FFFFFF?text=Sustainable+University+Campus" alt="A green, sustainable university campus" class="w-full h-auto object-cover rounded-xl">
        </div>

        <!-- Main Content Area -->
        <main class="space-y-8">

            <!-- Introduction -->
            <section id="introduction" class="bg-gray-50 rounded-2xl p-6">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4">1. Introduction</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                    Sustainability is a key global issue, and education is vital in shaping future leaders. Universities play an important role, but student awareness is often low. This study examines how lecturers, peers, activities, curriculum, and information sources influence awareness, with student attitude as a mediator.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- Problem Statement -->
            <section id="problem" class="bg-blue-50 rounded-2xl p-6">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-800 mb-4">2. Problem Statement</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                    <li>Uneven awareness of sustainability concepts and initiatives.</li>
                    <li>Focus mostly on knowledge, not attitudes.</li>
                    <li>Limited research on lecturer, peers, activities, curriculum, and information sources.</li>
                    <li>Need a holistic model linking external influences to student attitudes and awareness.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Research Objectives -->
            <section id="objectives" class="bg-gray-50 rounded-2xl p-6">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4">3. Research Objectives</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-600">
                    <li>Evaluate direct effects between independent variables and awareness.</li>
                    <li>Evaluate direct effects between independent variables on student attitudes.</li>
                    <li>Assess the role of student attitudes on awareness.</li>
                    <li>Examine the mediating role of attitudes.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Research Questions -->
            <section id="questions" class="bg-gray-50 rounded-2xl p-6">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4">4. Research Questions</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-600">
                    <li>Do lecturer, peer, activity, curriculum, and information sources affect awareness?</li>
                    <li>Do they influence student attitudes?</li>
                    <li>Do student attitudes affect awareness?</li>
                    <li>Do attitudes mediate the relationship?</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
            
            <!-- Theoretical and Conceptual Framework -->
            <section id="framework" class="bg-blue-50 rounded-2xl p-6">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-800 mb-4">5. Theoretical and Conceptual Framework</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                    This research is grounded in the <strong>Value-Belief-Norm (VBN) Theory</strong>, which suggests that an individual's values lead to certain beliefs, which in turn shape their attitudes and behavior. Our conceptual framework extends this theory to educational sustainability, proposing that external influences, such as lecturers, peers, activities, curriculum, and information sources, are the <strong>independent variables</strong>.
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                    The framework suggests that student <strong>attitudes</strong> act as a <strong>mediator</strong>, bridging the gap between these external influences and the final outcome of student awareness. This means that the effect of the independent variables on awareness is also channeled through student attitudes, which are the <strong>dependent variable</strong>.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- Hypothesis Development -->
            <section id="hypothesis" class="bg-gray-50 rounded-2xl p-6">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4">6. Hypothesis Development</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4 font-semibold">
                    The following hypotheses were developed:
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-600">
                    <li><strong>Direct Effects:</strong></li>
                    <li>H1: Lecturer experience on sustainability has a significant effect on students' awareness.</li>
                    <li>H2: Peer influence has a significant effect on students' awareness.</li>
                    <li>H3: Participation in sustainability-related activities has a significant effect on students' awareness.</li>
                    <li>H4: Curriculum exposure has a significant effect on students' awareness.</li>
                    <li>H5: Information sources have a significant effect on students' awareness.</li>
                    <li><strong>Mediating Effects:</strong></li>
                    <li>H6-H10: Lecturer, Peer, Participation, Curriculum, and Information Sources influence students' awareness through the mediating effect of Student Attitudes.</li>
                    <li>H11: Student Attitudes have a significant effect on students' awareness.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Research Methodology -->
            <section id="methodology" class="bg-gray-50 rounded-2xl p-6">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4">7. Research Methodology</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-2 font-semibold">
                    This study adopted a quantitative, cross-sectional survey design.
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-600">
                    <li><span class="font-semibold">Sample:</span> The target population was undergraduate and postgraduate students at the UniKL Business School.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-semibold">Data Collection:</span> A questionnaire was used, employing a 5-point Likert scale.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-semibold">Analysis:</span> The data was analyzed using SPSS and SmartPLS, employing the Partial Least Squares Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM) approach to test the mediation hypotheses.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Conclusion -->
            <section id="conclusion" class="bg-blue-50 rounded-2xl p-6">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-800 mb-4">8. Conclusion</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-800 leading-relaxed">
                    Awareness is shaped by institutional, social, and individual influences, with attitudes as the key bridge. Higher Education Institutions can enhance this awareness through lecturer training, peer initiatives, curriculum integration, and credible information.
                </p>
            </section>
        </main>

        <!-- Footer Section -->
